"# Chapter 13: Nested Wire-Shots

You've learned to collapse a single wire call into one atomic form—fetch, transform, use, all closed by the same paren that opened the journey. Now double it: two wire calls, one nested inside the other, still expressed as a single top-level form. The outer call waits for the inner; the inner closes with data that the outer immediately consumes. No intermediate variable. No orphaned state between hops. No latency compounding across a seam.

This is the nested wire-shot: one form, two flights, zero gaps.

Why it matters in Motoi: a recipe site returns an ingredient list; a second call fetches the pantry inventory for each ingredient; the final answer—\"can I make this?\"—lands in one atomic expression. A news API returns a headline; a knowledge lookup fills the context; the composed summary surfaces in one shot. The disposition we're drilling: when two wire calls depend on each other, nest them in place rather than sequencing them across statements.

The chapter opens gently—simple pairs where the dependency is obvious—and climbs toward genuinely hard nests where three or four calls close each other in a single form.

---

## The Simplest Nest

A city name comes back from one wire call. A weather lookup needs that city. Instead of storing the city in a variable and calling weather in a second statement, nest the city fetch inside the weather call. One form. Two hops. The inner call closes the outer.

```scheme
(surface :say \"Current temperature: ~a°F\"
  :from (fetch (string-append \"https://api.weather.local/temp?city=\"
                              (fetch \"https://api.location.local/city\"))))
```

The inner `(fetch …)` runs first, returns a city string, and immediately closes the URL being built by `string-append`. The outer `fetch` fires with the complete URL. The temperature string closes the `:from` slot. One paren closes the whole interaction.

---

## Nest a Knowledge Lookup Inside a Query

A wire call returns a species name. A local knowledge lookup needs that species to answer a habitat question. Nest the wire call inside the knowledge form.

```scheme
(knowledge/of :category \"habitat\"
              :subject (fetch \"https://api.nature.local/species/random\"))
```

The fetch runs, returns `\"peregrine falcon\"` (or any species), and that string immediately closes the `:subject` slot. The knowledge lookup fires with the complete argument. One form. Two data sources—one remote, one local—both closed by the same outer paren.

---

## Nest a Recall Inside a Wire Call

A speech template needs a topic summary. That summary lives in cortex. The final result gets sent over the wire to a logging service. Nest the recall inside the wire post.

```scheme
(fetch \"https://api.log.local/entry\"
       :method 'POST
       :body (cortex/recall :topic \"favorite-color\"))
```

The `(cortex/recall …)` runs first, returns the stored value, and immediately closes the `:body` slot. The `fetch` fires with the complete POST payload. One form. Two retrievals—one from cortex, one to the wire—nested without intermediate state.

---

## Nest a Computation Inside a Fetch

A conversion endpoint needs a Celsius value. The Celsius value comes from a Fahrenheit fetch. Nest the fetch inside the arithmetic that closes the second URL.

```scheme
(fetch (string-append \"https://api.convert.local/c-to-k?c=\"
                      (number->string
                        (/ (- (string->number
                                (fetch \"https://api.weather.local/temp-f?city=Portland\"))
                              32)
                           1.8))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a Fahrenheit string. `string->number` converts it. The arithmetic `(/ (- … 32) 1.8)` produces Celsius. `number->string` serializes it. `string-append` builds the Kelvin query URL. The outer fetch fires. One form. Four transformations. Two wire hops. Zero intermediate variables.

---

## Nest Two Knowledge Lookups

A question about \"predators of X\" where X comes from a knowledge lookup about \"most common rodent in Y\" and Y comes from a wire call returning a biome name.

```scheme
(knowledge/of :category \"predators\"
              :subject (knowledge/of :category \"common-rodent\"
                                     :subject (fetch \"https://api.geo.local/biome?lat=45.5&lon=-122.6\")))
```

The innermost fetch returns `\"temperate rainforest\"`. The middle knowledge lookup returns `\"deer mouse\"`. The outer knowledge lookup returns `\"owls, snakes, foxes\"`. Three lookups. One form. Each call closes the slot of the call that wraps it.

---

## Nest a Guard Inside a Nested Fetch

Only fetch the second resource if the first returns a non-empty result. Use `when` inside the outer form to guard the second hop.

```scheme
(when (not (string=? (fetch \"https://api.feature.local/enabled?flag=new-ui\") \"\"))
  (fetch (string-append \"https://api.assets.local/bundle?name=\"
                        (fetch \"https://api.feature.local/enabled?flag=new-ui\"))))
```

The first fetch runs. If it returns an empty string, the `when` short-circuits and the whole form returns `#f`. If it returns a feature name, the second fetch fires with that name embedded in the URL. One form. One guard. Two wire hops only if the guard passes.

*[needs: short-circuit semantics for `when` across async fetch completions]*  
<!-- BUILD: runtime must not fire the consequent fetch if the guard fetch returns falsey -->

---

## Nest a Map Over Fetched Data

A wire call returns a list of city names (as a JSON array). Map a weather fetch over each city. The map closes the outer `surface :say` form.

```scheme
(surface :say \"Temperatures: ~a\"
  :from (map (lambda (city)
               (fetch (string-append \"https://api.weather.local/temp?city=\" city)))
             (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.geo.local/cities?region=PNW\"))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON string of city names. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `map` iterates, firing a weather fetch for each city. The resulting list of temperatures closes the `:from` slot. One form. Multiple wire hops (one + N). Zero intermediate accumulation outside the form.

*[needs: `json-parse` in stdlib and async-aware `map` that waits for all fetches]*  
<!-- BUILD: map must return a promise that resolves when all inner fetches complete -->

---

## Nest a Filtered Fetch Result Inside Another Call

Fetch a list of product IDs. Filter for IDs above 1000. Fetch details for the first match. Return the product name.

```scheme
(let ((id (car (filter (lambda (n) (> n 1000))
                       (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.store.local/products/ids\"))))))
  (json-ref (fetch (string-append \"https://api.store.local/products/\" (number->string id)))
            \"name\"))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array of IDs. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `filter` keeps IDs > 1000. `car` takes the first. `number->string` serializes it. `string-append` builds the detail URL. The second fetch fires. `json-ref` extracts the name field. One `let` binds the filtered ID; the body is still a single composed expression. One top-level form.

*[needs: `json-ref` accessor in stdlib]*  
<!-- BUILD: (json-ref parsed-json \"key\") returns the value at key or 'nan -->

---

## Nest a Fold Over Fetched Data Inside a POST

Fetch a list of numbers. Fold them into a sum. POST the sum to a logging endpoint. One form.

```scheme
(fetch \"https://api.log.local/sum\"
       :method 'POST
       :body (number->string
               (fold + 0 (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.math.local/numbers\")))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array of numbers. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `fold` sums them. `number->string` serializes the result. The outer fetch POSTs it. One form. Three transformations. Two wire hops. The fold closes the `:body` slot; the body closes the POST.

---

## Nest Recall Inside a Conditional Inside a Fetch

If a user preference is set, fetch a personalized resource; otherwise fetch the default. Nest the recall inside the conditional inside the URL builder.

```scheme
(fetch (string-append \"https://api.content.local/\"
                      (if (cortex/recall :topic \"premium-user\")
                          \"premium/feed\"
                          \"standard/feed\")))
```

The `(cortex/recall …)` runs first, returns `#t` or `#f`. The `if` selects the path segment. `string-append` builds the URL. The fetch fires. One form. One recall. One wire hop. The conditional closes the URL; the URL closes the fetch.

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Case Dispatch

A registry lookup returns a capability tier. A `case` dispatch selects which analytics endpoint to call. Nest the registry call inside the `case` test, and nest each fetch inside its branch.

```scheme
(case (system/registry :domain \"analytics-tier\")
  ((premium) (fetch \"https://api.analytics.local/premium/event\" :method 'POST :body \"signup\"))
  ((standard) (fetch \"https://api.analytics.local/standard/event\" :method 'POST :body \"signup\"))
  (else 'nan))
```

The `(system/registry …)` runs first, returns a symbol like `'premium`. The `case` matches the branch. The corresponding fetch fires. One form. One registry lookup. One wire hop. The case closes the fetch; the fetch closes the form.

---

## Triple Nest: Fetch, Knowledge, Fetch

A product category comes from a wire call. A knowledge lookup maps the category to a warehouse region. A second wire call fetches inventory for that region. Three lookups, one form.

```scheme
(fetch (string-append \"https://api.inventory.local/stock?region=\"
                      (knowledge/of :category \"warehouse-region\"
                                    :subject (fetch \"https://api.catalog.local/product/category?id=8472\"))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a category string like `\"electronics\"`. The knowledge lookup returns a region code like `\"west\"`. `string-append` builds the inventory URL. The outer fetch fires. One form. Three data sources—two remote, one local—all closed by the same top-level paren.

---

## Nest Four Calls: Fetch, Parse, Filter, Fetch

Fetch a JSON array of user IDs. Parse it. Filter for IDs divisible by 10. Fetch profile details for the first match. Return the username.

```scheme
(json-ref (fetch (string-append \"https://api.users.local/profile?id=\"
                                (number->string
                                  (car (filter (lambda (n) (= (modulo n 10) 0))
                                               (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.users.local/ids\")))))))
          \"username\")
```

Four transformations: fetch, parse, filter, fetch. The innermost fetch returns a JSON string. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `filter` keeps IDs divisible by 10. `car` takes the first. `number->string` serializes it. `string-append` builds the profile URL. The second fetch fires. `json-ref` extracts the username. One form. Two wire hops. Four transformations. Zero intermediate bindings outside the expression.

---

## Nest a Conditional Wire-Shot Inside Another Conditional

If a feature flag is enabled (first fetch), and if the user is premium (recall), fetch the premium content; otherwise fetch standard. Two guards, two fetches, one form.

```scheme
(if (and (string=? (fetch \"https://api.feature.local/enabled?flag=premium-content\") \"true\")
         (cortex/recall :topic \"premium-user\"))
    (fetch \"https://api.content.local/premium\")
    (fetch \"https://api.content.local/standard\"))
```

The first fetch checks the feature flag. The recall checks the user tier. `and` short-circuits if either is false. The `if` selects the content fetch. One form. Up to three lookups (one wire, one recall, one wire). The guards close the `if`; the `if` closes the consequent fetch.

*[needs: async `and` that short-circuits without firing subsequent fetches if an earlier operand is false]*  
<!-- BUILD: and/or must handle promises and not start downstream fetches if upstream returns falsey -->

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Let-Bound Transformation

Fetch a temperature in Kelvin. Bind the conversion factor in a `let`. Return the Fahrenheit value as a formatted string. One form (the `let` is the top-level form; the body is a single expression).

```scheme
(let ((k (string->number (fetch \"https://api.weather.local/temp-k?city=Seattle\"))))
  (string-append (number->string (+ (* (- k 273.15) 1.8) 32)) \"°F\"))
```

The fetch runs, returns a Kelvin string. `string->number` converts it. The `let` binds `k`. The body computes Fahrenheit and formats it. One `let` form. One fetch. One transformation. The fetch closes the binding; the transformation closes the body.

---

## Nest a Fold Over Two Fetched Lists

Fetch a list of prices. Fetch a list of quantities. Zip them and fold to compute total cost. POST the result.

```scheme
(fetch \"https://api.orders.local/total\"
       :method 'POST
       :body (number->string
               (fold (lambda (pair acc)
                       (+ acc (* (car pair) (cdr pair))))
                     0
                     (map cons
                          (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.orders.local/prices\"))
                          (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.orders.local/quantities\"))))))
```

Two fetches return JSON arrays. Two `json-parse` calls convert them to lists. `map cons` zips the lists into pairs. `fold` accumulates the sum of `(price * quantity)` for each pair. `number->string` serializes the total. The outer fetch POSTs it. One form. Two wire reads. One wire write. The fold closes the `:body`; the body closes the POST.

*[needs: `map` must accept multiple lists and zip them]*  
<!-- BUILD: (map proc list1 list2 ...) should zip lists and apply proc to each tuple -->

---

## Nest a Recursive Fetch Chain

Fetch a paginated API. If the response includes a `next` URL, fetch it recursively. Return all accumulated items. (Use named `let` for recursion within a single top-level form.)

```scheme
(let fetch-all ((url \"https://api.data.local/items?page=1\")
                (acc '()))
  (let ((resp (json-parse (fetch url))))
    (let ((items (json-ref resp \"items\"))
          (next (json-ref resp \"next\")))
      (if next
          (fetch-all next (append acc items))
          (append acc items)))))
```

Named `let` establishes the recursive loop. The first fetch runs. The response is parsed. Items and the next-page URL are extracted. If `next` exists, recurse with the new URL and accumulated items. Otherwise return the final accumulation. One top-level form (the named `let`). Multiple wire hops (unknown count until `next` is null). Zero intermediate state outside the recursion.

*[needs: async recursion where each `fetch` returns a promise and `let`-bound values wait for promise resolution]*  
<!-- BUILD: named let must support async recursion with promise-returning fetch -->

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Guarded Map

Fetch a list of city names. For each city, fetch weather only if the city name is longer than 5 characters. Return the list of temperatures (with `'nan` for skipped cities).

```scheme
(map (lambda (city)
       (if (> (string-length city) 5)
           (fetch (string-append \"https://api.weather.local/temp?city=\" city))
           'nan))
     (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.geo.local/cities?region=EU\")))
```

The inner fetch returns a JSON array of city names. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `map` iterates. For each city, the guard checks length. If long enough, fetch temperature; otherwise return `'nan`. The map closes the outer form. One top-level `map`. One + N wire hops (where N is the number of long city names). Zero intermediate accumulation outside the `map`.

---

## Nest a Knowledge Lookup Inside a Filtered Map

Fetch a list of animal names. For each animal, look up its habitat. Filter the results to keep only \"forest\" animals. Return the filtered list.

```scheme
(filter (lambda (pair) (string=? (cdr pair) \"forest\"))
        (map (lambda (animal)
               (cons animal (knowledge/of :category \"habitat\" :subject animal)))
             (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.nature.local/animals\"))))
```

The fetch returns a JSON array of animal names. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `map` iterates, performing a knowledge lookup for each animal and pairing the animal name with its habitat. `filter` keeps only pairs where the habitat is `\"forest\"`. One form. One wire hop. N knowledge lookups. The filter closes the map; the map closes the fetch.

---

## Nest a Recall Inside a Let Inside a Fetch POST

Fetch a username from a wire call. Recall a stored auth token. Combine them in a JSON payload. POST to a login endpoint. One form.

```scheme
(let ((username (fetch \"https://api.auth.local/username\"))
      (token (cortex/recall :topic \"auth-token\")))
  (fetch \"https://api.auth.local/login\"
         :method 'POST
         :body (string-append \"{\\\"username\\\":\\\"\" username \"\\\",\\\"token\\\":\\\"\" token \"\\\"}\")))
```

The `let` binds two values: one from a wire call, one from cortex recall. The body constructs a JSON string and POSTs it. One `let` form (the top-level). One wire read. One recall. One wire write. The bindings close the body; the body closes the POST.

---

## Nest a Case Dispatch Over a Fetched Status Code

Fetch a health-check endpoint that returns a status code as a string. Dispatch on the code: if \"200\", fetch the main resource; if \"503\", return an error message; otherwise return `'nan`.

```scheme
(case (fetch \"https://api.service.local/health\")
  ((\"200\") (fetch \"https://api.service.local/data\"))
  ((\"503\") \"Service unavailable\")
  (else 'nan))
```

The first fetch runs, returns a string like `\"200\"`. The `case` matches the string. The corresponding branch fires. If `\"200\"`, the second fetch runs. One form. Up to two wire hops. The case closes the consequent fetch; the fetch closes the form.

*[needs: `case` matching on strings, not just symbols]*  
<!-- BUILD: case should support string literals in addition to symbol literals -->

---

## Nest Three Wire Calls in a Chain

Fetch a user ID. Use it to fetch a profile. Use the profile's region field to fetch regional settings. Return the timezone.

```scheme
(json-ref (fetch (string-append \"https://api.settings.local/region?code=\"
                                (json-ref (fetch (string-append \"https://api.users.local/profile?id=\"
                                                                (fetch \"https://api.auth.local/user-id\")))
                                          \"region\")))
          \"timezone\")
```

Three fetches. The innermost returns a user ID string. The middle fetch returns a JSON profile. `json-ref` extracts the region code. The outer fetch returns regional settings. `json-ref` extracts the timezone. One form. Three wire hops. Six transformations. Zero intermediate bindings outside the nesting.

---

## Nest a Fold Inside a Fetch POST with a Guarded Map

Fetch a list of transaction amounts. Filter out negative values. Sum the remaining amounts. POST the total to a reporting endpoint.

```scheme
(fetch \"https://api.reports.local/total\"
       :method 'POST
       :body (number->string
               (fold + 0
                     (filter (lambda (n) (>= n 0))
                             (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.transactions.local/amounts\"))))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array of numbers. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `filter` keeps non-negative values. `fold` sums them. `number->string` serializes the result. The outer fetch POSTs it. One form. Five transformations. Two wire hops. The fold closes the `:body`; the body closes the POST.

---

## Nest a Conditional Fetch Based on Two Recalls

If the user has both \"premium\" and \"early-access\" flags set in cortex, fetch the beta resource; otherwise fetch the stable resource.

```scheme
(if (and (cortex/recall :topic \"premium\")
         (cortex/recall :topic \"early-access\"))
    (fetch \"https://api.content.local/beta\")
    (fetch \"https://api.content.local/stable\"))
```

Two recalls. One `and`. One `if`. Two possible fetches. One form. The recalls close the `and`; the `and` closes the `if`; the `if` closes the consequent fetch.

---

## Nest a Map Over a Filtered Knowledge Lookup Result

Look up all animals in the \"endangered\" category (assume it returns a list). For each, fetch a photo URL from a wire endpoint. Return the list of URLs.

```scheme
(map (lambda (animal)
       (fetch (string-append \"https://api.photos.local/animal?name=\" animal)))
     (knowledge/of :category \"endangered-species\"))
```

The knowledge lookup returns a list of animal names. `map` iterates, building a URL and fetching a photo for each. The map closes the outer form. One top-level `map`. One knowledge lookup. N wire hops. Zero intermediate state.

*[needs: `knowledge/of` returning a list when :category matches multiple entries]*  
<!-- BUILD: knowledge/of should return a list of subjects when category is queried without :subject -->

