## Nest a Fetch Inside a Let* with Dependent Bindings

Fetch a product ID. Use it to fetch a product name. Use the name to fetch reviews. Return the count of reviews.

```scheme
(let* ((id (fetch \"https://api.catalog.local/product/id?sku=A987\"))
       (name (json-ref (fetch (string-append \"https://api.catalog.local/product?id=\" id))
                       \"name\"))
       (reviews (json-parse (fetch (string-append \"https://api.reviews.local/list?product=\" name)))))
  (length reviews))
```

`let*` binds three values sequentially, each depending on the prior. Three fetches. Three transformations. The body computes the review count. One `let*` form (the top-level). Three wire hops. The final binding closes the body; the body closes the `length` call.

---

## Nest a Cond Dispatch Over a Fetched Configuration

Fetch a config value. Use `cond` to dispatch on the value: if \"alpha\", fetch alpha resources; if \"beta\", fetch beta; otherwise return `'nan`.

```scheme
(cond
  ((string=? (fetch \"https://api.config.local/env\") \"alpha\")
   (fetch \"https://api.resources.local/alpha\"))
  ((string=? (fetch \"https://api.config.local/env\") \"beta\")
   (fetch \"https://api.resources.local/beta\"))
  (else 'nan))
```

The fetch runs twice (once per test clause). If \"alpha\" matches, the first consequent fetch fires. If \"beta\" matches, the second fires. Otherwise `'nan`. One `cond` form. Up to three wire hops. The tests close the consequent fetches; the cond closes the form.

*[needs: cond should memoize the fetched value across test clauses to avoid duplicate fetches]*  
<!-- BUILD: cond must not re-evaluate a fetch expression in multiple test clauses — bind it once and test the result -->

Better form to avoid duplicate fetch:

```scheme
(let ((env (fetch \"https://api.config.local/env\")))
  (cond
    ((string=? env \"alpha\") (fetch \"https://api.resources.local/alpha\"))
    ((string=? env \"beta\") (fetch \"https://api.resources.local/beta\"))
    (else 'nan)))
```

One `let` form. One fetch bound, tested twice. Up to two wire hops total. The cond closes the consequent fetch; the let closes the cond.

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Recursive Countdown

Count down from a fetched number to zero, logging each step to a wire endpoint. Use named `let` for recursion. One form.

```scheme
(let countdown ((n (string->number (fetch \"https://api.math.local/random-int?max=10\"))))
  (if (<= n 0)
      'done
      (begin
        (fetch \"https://api.log.local/event\" :method 'POST :body (number->string n))
        (countdown (- n 1)))))
```

The fetch returns a random integer as a string. `string->number` converts it. Named `let` starts the countdown. Each iteration POSTs the current number to the log endpoint, then recurses with `n - 1`. When `n` reaches zero, return `'done`. One top-level named `let`. One initial fetch. N POST fetches (where N is the random integer). Zero intermediate state outside the recursion.

*[needs: `begin` supporting multiple expressions in a form, and async recursion]*  
<!-- BUILD: begin must sequence async fetch calls and wait for each before continuing -->

---

## Nest a Filter Inside a Fold Inside a POST

Fetch a list of scores. Filter out scores below 50. Compute the average of the remaining scores. POST the average to a summary endpoint.

```scheme
(fetch \"https://api.summary.local/average\"
       :method 'POST
       :body (number->string
               (let ((passing (filter (lambda (n) (>= n 50))
                                      (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.scores.local/list\")))))
                 (/ (fold + 0 passing) (length passing)))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array of scores. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `filter` keeps scores >= 50. The `let` binds the filtered list. `fold` sums the scores. `length` counts them. Division computes the average. `number->string` serializes it. The outer fetch POSTs it. One `let` form (containing the POST). One wire read. One wire write. The fold closes the average computation; the computation closes the `:body`; the body closes the POST.

---

## Nest Two Knowledge Lookups and a Fetch

Look up the capital city of a country (from a fetched country code). Look up the timezone of that city. Fetch current time for that timezone.

```scheme
(fetch (string-append \"https://api.time.local/now?tz=\"
                      (knowledge/of :category \"timezone\"
                                    :subject (knowledge/of :category \"capital\"
                                                           :subject (fetch \"https://api.geo.local/country-code?ip=203.0.113.42\")))))
```

Three nested lookups: fetch, knowledge, knowledge. The fetch returns a country code like `\"FR\"`. The first knowledge lookup returns `\"Paris\"`. The second knowledge lookup returns `\"Europe/Paris\"`. `string-append` builds the time query URL. The outer fetch returns the current time. One form. One wire read. Two knowledge lookups. One wire read. Zero intermediate bindings.

---

## Nest a Map with a Let-Bound Fetched Value

Fetch a currency conversion rate. Map over a list of prices (also fetched) to convert each price using the rate. Return the converted list.

```scheme
(let ((rate (string->number (fetch \"https://api.currency.local/rate?from=USD&to=EUR\"))))
  (map (lambda (price) (* price rate))
       (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.prices.local/list?currency=USD\"))))
```

The first fetch returns a conversion rate as a string. `string->number` converts it. The `let` binds `rate`. The second fetch returns a JSON array of prices. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `map` multiplies each price by the rate. One `let` form. Two fetches. One map. The map closes the body; the body closes the `let`.

---

## Nest a Guarded Fetch Inside a Fold

Fetch a list of product IDs. For each ID, fetch stock quantity if the ID is even; otherwise use zero. Sum the quantities.

```scheme
(fold (lambda (id acc)
        (+ acc (if (even? id)
                   (string->number (fetch (string-append \"https://api.inventory.local/stock?id=\" (number->string id))))
                   0)))
      0
      (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.catalog.local/product-ids\")))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array of IDs. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `fold` iterates. For each ID, if even, fetch the stock quantity and add it to the accumulator; otherwise add zero. One form. One initial fetch. Up to N additional fetches (where N is the count of even IDs). The fold closes the sum; the sum closes the form.

---

## Nest a Case Dispatch Over a Knowledge Lookup Inside a Fetch

Look up a user's subscription tier from knowledge. Use `case` to select which analytics event to POST based on the tier.

```scheme
(case (knowledge/of :category \"subscription-tier\" :subject \"user:4523\")
  ((free) (fetch \"https://api.analytics.local/event/free-action\" :method 'POST :body \"click\"))
  ((premium) (fetch \"https://api.analytics.local/event/premium-action\" :method 'POST :body \"click\"))
  (else 'nan))
```

The knowledge lookup returns a symbol like `'free`. The `case` matches the branch. The corresponding POST fires. One form. One knowledge lookup. One wire hop. The case closes the consequent fetch; the fetch closes the form.

---

## Nest a Fold Over Two Fetched and Zipped Lists with a Guard

Fetch prices. Fetch availability flags. Zip them. Fold to sum prices only for available items.

```scheme
(fold (lambda (pair acc)
        (if (cdr pair)
            (+ acc (car pair))
            acc))
      0
      (map cons
           (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.prices.local/list\"))
           (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.availability.local/list\"))))
```

Two fetches return JSON arrays. Two `json-parse` calls convert them to lists. `map cons` zips them into pairs `(price . available?)`. `fold` iterates: if the item is available (cdr is truthy), add the price to the accumulator; otherwise skip. One form. Two wire reads. One fold. The fold closes the sum; the sum closes the form.

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Let with a Conditional Guard

Fetch a feature flag. If enabled, bind a resource URL from a second fetch; otherwise bind a default URL. Use the bound URL in a final expression.

```scheme
(let ((url (if (string=? (fetch \"https://api.feature.local/enabled?flag=new-search\") \"true\")
               (fetch \"https://api.config.local/search-url?version=new\")
               \"https://api.search.local/default\")))
  (string-append \"Search at: \" url))
```

The first fetch checks the feature flag. The `if` fires either the second fetch or returns a hardcoded string. The `let` binds `url`. The body formats a message. One `let` form. Up to two wire hops. The conditional closes the binding; the body closes the `let`.

---

## Nest Four Calls: Fetch, Knowledge, Filter, Fetch

Fetch a biome name. Look up common animals in that biome. Filter for animals longer than 6 characters. Fetch photos for each filtered animal. Return the list of photo URLs.

```scheme
(map (lambda (animal)
       (fetch (string-append \"https://api.photos.local/animal?name=\" animal)))
     (filter (lambda (name) (> (string-length name) 6))
             (knowledge/of :category \"common-animals\"
                           :subject (fetch \"https://api.geo.local/biome?region=PNW\"))))
```

Four nested transformations: fetch, knowledge, filter, map (with nested fetch in the map body). The innermost fetch returns a biome name. The knowledge lookup returns a list of animals. `filter` keeps animals with names longer than 6 characters. `map` fires a photo fetch for each. One form. One initial fetch. One knowledge lookup. N photo fetches. Zero intermediate bindings outside the nesting.

---

## Nest a Recursive Fetch with a Conditional Stopping Condition

Fetch a paginated list. Continue fetching the `next` page until the response has no `next` field or until 5 pages have been fetched. Accumulate all items.

```scheme
(let fetch-pages ((url \"https://api.data.local/items?page=1\")
                  (acc '())
                  (count 0))
  (if (>= count 5)
      acc
      (let ((resp (json-parse (fetch url))))
        (let ((items (json-ref resp \"items\"))
              (next (json-ref resp \"next\")))
          (if next
              (fetch-pages next (append acc items) (+ count 1))
              (append acc items))))))
```

Named `let` with a page counter. Each iteration fetches a page. If the counter reaches 5, stop and return the accumulator. Otherwise parse the response, extract items and the next URL. If next exists, recurse; otherwise return the final accumulation. One top-level named `let`. Up to 5 wire hops. Zero intermediate state outside the recursion.

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Cond with Multiple Guards

Fetch a status code. Use `cond` to dispatch: if \"200\", fetch data; if \"404\", return an error message; if \"500\", fetch a fallback resource; otherwise return `'nan`.

```scheme
(let ((status (fetch \"https://api.service.local/status\")))
  (cond
    ((string=? status \"200\") (fetch \"https://api.service.local/data\"))
    ((string=? status \"404\") \"Not found\")
    ((string=? status \"500\") (fetch \"https://api.service.local/fallback\"))
    (else 'nan)))
```

The `let` binds the status from a fetch. The `cond` tests the status and fires the appropriate branch. One `let` form. Up to two wire hops (status + one branch fetch). The cond closes the consequent fetch; the let closes the cond.

---

## Nest a Fold Over Fetched Data with a Let-Bound Coefficient

Fetch a multiplier from a config endpoint. Fetch a list of base values. Multiply each by the multiplier and sum the results.

```scheme
(let ((mult (string->number (fetch \"https://api.config.local/multiplier\"))))
  (fold (lambda (n acc) (+ acc (* n mult)))
        0
        (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.data.local/values\"))))
```

The first fetch returns the multiplier. `string->number` converts it. The `let` binds `mult`. The second fetch returns a JSON array. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `fold` multiplies each value by `mult` and accumulates the sum. One `let` form. Two fetches. One fold. The fold closes the body; the body closes the `let`.

---

## Nest a Fetch Inside a Filtered Map with a Knowledge Guard

Fetch a list of city names. For each city, look up the country. Filter to keep only cities in \"USA\". For each remaining city, fetch the population. Return the list of populations.

```scheme
(map (lambda (city)
       (string->number (fetch (string-append \"https://api.geo.local/population?city=\" city))))
     (filter (lambda (city)
               (string=? (knowledge/of :category \"country\" :subject city) \"USA\"))
             (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.geo.local/cities\"))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array of city names. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `filter` iterates, performing a knowledge lookup for each city and keeping only those in \"USA\". `map` fetches population for each remaining city. One form. One initial fetch. N knowledge lookups (where N is the total city count). M population fetches (where M is the USA city count). Zero intermediate bindings outside the pipeline.

---

## Nest a Fold with a Conditional Accumulation Inside a POST

Fetch a list of transaction amounts. Fold to sum only the positive amounts. POST the sum to a reporting endpoint.

```scheme
(fetch \"https://api.reports.local/positive-sum\"
       :method 'POST
       :body (number->string
               (fold (lambda (n acc)
                       (if (> n 0) (+ acc n) acc))
                     0
                     (json-parse (fetch \"https://api.transactions.local/amounts\")))))
```

The innermost fetch returns a JSON array. `json-parse` converts it to a list. `fold` iterates: if the value is positive, add it to the accumulator; otherwise leave the accumulator unchanged. `number->string` serializes the result. The outer fetch POSTs it. One form. Two wire hops. The fold closes the `:body`; the body closes the POST.

---

## Nest Two Fetches with a Let-Bound Transformation Between Them

Fetch a raw CSV string. Parse it into a list (assume a `csv-parse` function). Fetch metadata for the first row's ID. Return the metadata.

```scheme
(let ((rows (csv-parse (fetch \"https://api.data.local/export.csv\"))))
  (json-parse (fetch (string-append \"https://api.meta.local/info?id=\" (car (car rows))))))
```

The first fetch returns a CSV string. `csv-parse` converts it to a list of lists. The `let` binds `rows`. `car (car rows)` extracts the first cell (an ID). `string-append` builds the metadata URL. The second fetch returns JSON. `json-parse` converts it. One `let` form. Two fetches. The fetch closes the `json-parse`; the parse closes the body; the body closes the `let`.

*[needs: `csv-parse` in stdlib]*  
<!-- BUILD: (csv-parse string) returns a list of lists, one per row -->

